Spreadsheets - Excel

  1. In an Excel file, create the following dataset and save it as survey.xlsx.(Its in the folder data) Then, read it into R, with survey_id as a character variable and n_pets as a numerical variable. 
survey <- read_excel(
  "data/survey.xlsx",
  col_types = c("text", "numeric")
  )
## Warning: Expecting numeric in B4 / R4C2: got 'N/A'
## Warning: Expecting numeric in B5 / R5C2: got 'two'
survey
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   survey_id n_pets
##   <chr>      <dbl>
## 1 1.0            0
## 2 2.0            1
## 3 3.0           NA
## 4 4.0           NA
## 5 5.0            2
## 6 6.0           NA
# We can see some issues. When changing a number to text we get an unnecessary floating point "number" of 1.0, 2.0 etc. `n_pets` also mixes text with numbers and there is an N/A value followed by an empty cell which I imagine also should be considered a missing value. Lets fix a few things up.

survey <- read_excel(
  "data/survey.xlsx",
  na = c("", "N/A"),
  col_types = c("text", "text")
  )
survey
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   survey_id n_pets
##   <chr>     <chr> 
## 1 1.0       0.0   
## 2 2.0       1.0   
## 3 3.0       <NA>  
## 4 4.0       two   
## 5 5.0       2.0   
## 6 6.0       <NA>
survey <- survey |>
  mutate(
    n_pets = if_else(n_pets == "two", "2", n_pets),
    n_pets = parse_number(n_pets),
    survey_id = str_replace(survey_id, "\\.0", "")
  )
survey
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   survey_id n_pets
##   <chr>      <dbl>
## 1 1              0
## 2 2              1
## 3 3             NA
## 4 4              2
## 5 5              2
## 6 6             NA
  1. In another Excel file, create the following dataset and save it as roster.xlsx. (Again in the folder data) Then, read it into R. The resulting data frame should be called roster and should look like the following.

#> # A tibble: 12 3 #> group subgroup id #> #> 1 1 A 1 #> 2 1 A 2 #> 3 1 A 3 #> 4 1 B 4 #> 5 1 B 5 #> 6 1 B 6 #> 7 1 B 7 #> 8 2 A 8 #> 9 2 A 9 #> 10 2 B 10 #> 11 2 B 11 #> 12 2 B 12

roster <- read_excel(
  "data/roster.xlsx",
  col_types = c("numeric", "text", "numeric")
  )
roster <- roster |> 
  fill(c(group, subgroup), .direction = "down")

  1. In a new Excel file, create the following dataset and save it as sales.xlsx. (Its in data folder)
    1. Read sales.xlsx in and save as sales. The data frame should look like the following, with id and n as column names and with 9 rows.

#> # A tibble: 9 2 #> id n
#> #> 1 Brand 1 n
#> 2 1234 8
#> 3 8721 2
#> 4 1822 3
#> 5 Brand 2 n
#> 6 3333 1
#> 7 2156 3
#> 8 3987 6
#> 9 3216 5

sales <- read_excel(
  "data/sales.xlsx",
  col_names = c("id", "n"),
  skip = 4,
  col_types = c("text", "text")
  )
sales
## # A tibble: 9  2
##   id      n    
##   <chr>   <chr>
## 1 Brand 1 n    
## 2 1234.0  8.0  
## 3 8721.0  2.0  
## 4 1822.0  3.0  
## 5 Brand 2 n    
## 6 3333.0  1.0  
## 7 2156.0  3.0  
## 8 3987.0  6.0  
## 9 3216.0  5.0
  1. Modify sales further to get it into the following tidy format with three columns (brand, id, and n) and 7 rows of data. Note that id and n are numeric, brand is a character variable.

#> # A tibble: 7 3 #> brand id n #> #> 1 Brand 1 1234 8 #> 2 Brand 1 8721 2 #> 3 Brand 1 1822 3 #> 4 Brand 2 3333 1 #> 5 Brand 2 2156 3 #> 6 Brand 2 3987 6 #> 7 Brand 2 3216 5

sales |> 
  slice(-c(1, 5)) |> 
  mutate(
    brand = rep(c("Brand 1", "Brand 2"), c(3, 4)),
    id = as.numeric(id),
    n = as.numeric(n)
    ) |> 
  relocate(brand)
## # A tibble: 7  3
##   brand      id     n
##   <chr>   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 Brand 1  1234     8
## 2 Brand 1  8721     2
## 3 Brand 1  1822     3
## 4 Brand 2  3333     1
## 5 Brand 2  2156     3
## 6 Brand 2  3987     6
## 7 Brand 2  3216     5
  1. Recreate the bake_sale data frame, write it out to an Excel file using the write.xlsx() function from the openxlsx package.
bake_sale <- tibble(
  item     = factor(c("brownie", "cupcake", "cookie")),
  quantity = c(10, 5, 8)
)

bake_sale
## # A tibble: 3  2
##   item    quantity
##   <fct>      <dbl>
## 1 brownie       10
## 2 cupcake        5
## 3 cookie         8
write_xlsx(bake_sale, path = "data/bake-sale.xlsx")
  1. In Chapter 7 you learned about the janitor::clean_names() function to turn column names into snake case. Read the students.xlsx file that we introduced earlier in this section and use this function to clean the column names.
students <- read_excel("data/students.xlsx")

students <- students |> 
  janitor::clean_names()
